### HTMX OOB Swaps with Thymeleaf Markup Selectors

Source: https://github.com/wimdeblauwe/htmx-spring-boot/blob/main/README.md

Demonstrates using Thymeleaf's Markup Selectors with htmx for Out-of-Band (OOB) swaps. It shows how to return specific fragments from templates using `HxRequest` and `FragmentsRendering`.

```java
import org.springframework.ui.Model;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.servlet.ModelAndView;
import java.util.Collection;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

// Assuming HxRequest annotation and FragmentsRendering are available
// import io.github.wimdeblauwe.htmx.spring.boot.thymeleaf.HxRequest;
// import io.github.wimdeblauwe.htmx.spring.boot.thymeleaf.FragmentsRendering;

@HxRequest
@GetMapping("/users")
public View users(Model model) {
    model.addAttribute("users", userRepository.findAll());
    model.addAttribute("count", userRepository.count());

    return FragmentsRendering
            .with("users :: list")
            .fragment("users :: count")
            .build();
}

@HxRequest
@GetMapping("/users")
public Collection<ModelAndView> test() {
    return List.of(
            new ModelAndView("users :: list", Map.of("users", userRepository.findAll())),
            new ModelAndView("users :: count", Map.of("count", userRepository.count()))
    );
}
```

--------------------------------

### Returning Multiple HTML Fragments with FragmentsRendering

Source: https://github.com/wimdeblauwe/htmx-spring-boot/blob/main/README.md

Shows how to return multiple HTML fragments from a Spring MVC controller using the `FragmentsRendering` class, enabling Out-of-Band Swaps in HTMX.

```java
@HxRequest
@GetMapping("/users")
public View users(Model model) {
    model.addAttribute("users", userRepository.findAll());
    model.addAttribute("count", userRepository.count());

    return FragmentsRendering
        .with("users/list")
        .fragment("users/count")
        .build();
}
```

--------------------------------

### Setting Htmx Headers and Redirect in a Spring Boot Controller

Source: https://github.com/wimdeblauwe/htmx-spring-boot/blob/main/README.md

An example of a Spring Boot controller method that updates a user, adds a success message, triggers an htmx event, and performs a client-side redirect using the 'redirect:htmx:/user/list' syntax.

```java
@HxRequest
@PostMapping("/user/{id}")
public String user(@PathVariable Long id, @ModelAttribute @Valid UserForm form, 
                 BindingResult bindingResult, RedirectAttributes redirectAttributes,
                 HtmxResponse htmxResponse) {

    if (bindingResult.hasErrors()) {
        return "user/form";
    }

    // update user ...
    redirectAttributes.addFlashAttribute("successMessage", "User has been successfully updated.");
    htmxResponse.addTrigger("user-updated");

    return "redirect:htmx:/user/list";
}
```

--------------------------------

### HTMX Response Header Annotations

Source: https://github.com/wimdeblauwe/htmx-spring-boot/blob/main/README.md

These annotations can be applied to controller methods to set specific HTMX response headers, influencing how HTMX processes the response. They are part of the `io.github.wimdeblauwe.htmx.spring.boot.mvc` package.

```APIDOC
HxLocation:
  Sets the HX-Location header to navigate the browser to a new URL.

HxPushUrl:
  Sets the HX-Push-Url header to push a new URL onto the browser's history stack.

HxRedirect:
  Sets the HX-Redirect header to redirect the browser to a new URL.

HxRefresh:
  Sets the HX-Refresh header to trigger a full page refresh.

HxReplaceUrl:
  Sets the HX-Replace-Url header to replace the current URL in the browser's history stack.

HxReselect:
  Sets the HX-Reselect header to select a different element to swap the response into.

HxReswap:
  Sets the HX-Reswap header to specify the swap strategy for the HTMX response.

HxRetarget:
  Sets the HX-Retarget header to select a different target element for the HTMX swap.

HxTrigger:
  Sets the HX-Trigger header to trigger a custom event after the response is processed.

HxTriggerAfterSettle:
  Sets the HX-Trigger-After-Settle header to trigger a custom event after HTMX settles.

HxTriggerAfterSwap:
  Sets the HX-Trigger-After-Swap header to trigger a custom event after the swap is complete.
```

--------------------------------

### HtmxResponse and Views for Response Headers

Source: https://github.com/wimdeblauwe/htmx-spring-boot/blob/main/README.md

Demonstrates setting htmx response headers using HtmxResponse and specific views for control flow headers like HX-Redirect, HX-Location, and HX-Refresh. It also covers special view name prefixes for these actions.

```APIDOC
HtmxResponse:
  - Allows setting various htmx response headers.
  - Can be used as a controller method argument.

HtmxRedirectView:
  - Sets the HX-Redirect header for client-side redirects.
  - Can be returned as a controller method's return value.

HtmxLocationRedirectView:
  - Sets the HX-Location header for client-side redirects without a full page reload.
  - Can be returned as a controller method's return value.

HtmxRefreshView:
  - Sets the HX-Refresh header to trigger a client-side page refresh.
  - Can be returned as a controller method's return value.

Special View Name Prefixes:
  - redirect:htmx:/path: Performs a client-side redirect to the specified URL.
  - redirect:htmx:location:/path: Performs a client-side redirect without reloading the entire page.
  - refresh:htmx: Refreshes the current page on the client-side.
```

